{"author":{"id":"977fec8a59c245f25e0e700fa290ef50836c624572869487e9e47fedc85061ee"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445082039,"nonce":"rwvOxxuf9h9w72NLdENuP3sX4yo=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODkwODkwOA==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148908908"},"message":"\u003e \u003e I wholeheartedly agree with @yhoogstrate reasoning. Best would be to have a header that is marked as comment, together with metadata that is equivalent to the header line. Is this possible?\n\u003e \n\u003e Yes, I think so.\n\u003e Still, imagine a file with 5 headers, the 5th is the column description and now you want to sort this file. Unfortunately, these files exist :(\n\nI didn't consider that case. Ideally galaxy would ignore things it recognised as headers (or comments),\nif the tool didn't specifically ask for the metadata information. But I can see how this gets complex very quickly.\n\n\u003e \u003e I know this would be larger change in the galaxy codebase, but would it be possible to have \"tool-specific datatypes\"? So for example featureCounts and htseq would produce tabular output of class CountTable, which would be a subclass of tabular, which would be defined within the tools datatypes.conf? Or maybe that is already possible and I'm re-inventing the wheel?\n\u003e \n\u003e Oh, yes this in discussed a lot. We can define a data type for count-data, but we can not even make this unique for htseq-count, featureCounts and DEXSeq-counts ;)\n\nWhy not? It's true we'd need to do this for htseq-count, featureCounts and DEXSeq-counts, but if we decide on a common datatype with common metadata, then we'd only need to map Identifiers and counts in the datatype. I'm a bit vague here, admittedly, but it would be nice if galaxy tools could transparently handle the native dataformats produced by htseq-count, featureCounts and DEXSeq-counts, since the kind of information they provide is the same.\n\nEDIT: When I mean \"galaxy could handle\", I mean galaxy tools and the datatypes they define.\nI don't think that kind of complexity should be part of galaxy.","files":null}]}